This article discusses the executive order issued by President Donald Trump on January 5, 2021, regarding the national emergency with respect to the information and communications technology and services supply chain. The order specifically focuses on the threat posed by Chinese connected software applications, which have the ability to access and capture sensitive personal and proprietary information from users. The order prohibits certain transactions with Chinese connected software applications, such as Alipay, CamScanner, QQ Wallet, SHAREit, Tencent QQ, VMate, WeChat Pay, and WPS Office. The Secretary of Commerce is directed to evaluate other Chinese connected software applications that may pose a risk to national security and take appropriate action. The order also requires the Secretary, in consultation with the Attorney General and the Director of National Intelligence, to provide recommendations on preventing the sale or transfer of US user data to foreign adversaries. The order authorizes the Secretary, in consultation with other officials, to take necessary actions to implement the order, and agencies are required to provide resources and assistance to the Department of Commerce for this purpose. The order includes definitions of relevant terms and contains general provisions regarding its implementation.